<subSubSection id="E1CF6787FFD5577DFF11F8933ADB3B9A" pageId="3" pageNumber="359" type="description">
<paragraph id="A96A340CFFD5577DFF11F8933C833B2D" blockId="3.[151,1437,1759,2038]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">
The wing pattern of the female are similar to that of the male, except that the two cell spots are perpendicular to costa, and there is a small triangular pale patch in the lower half of space CuA 
<quantity id="6E2D99E9FFD5577DFBD5F8A93D2C3B2E" box="[1027,1064,1831,1863]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="3" pageNumber="359" unit="in" value="2.0">
<subScript id="35513649FFD5577DFBD5F8A93D0F3B28" attach="left" box="[1027,1035,1849,1863]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">2</subScript>
in
</quantity>
opposite to the lower cell spot.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A96A340CFFD5577DFF11F8DB3ADB3B9A" blockId="3.[151,1437,1759,2038]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">
Female genitalia (
<figureCitation id="31EE2889FFD5577DFE40F8DB38E83B09" box="[406,492,1867,1894]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1123,1148]" captionTargetBox="[323,1249,180,1087]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[309,1265,174,1103]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 19. Female genitalia of Pedesta xiaoqingae. A. ventral view; B. lateral view; C. dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3548632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3548632/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
). Papillae anales reniform in ventral view, covered with long hairs. Lamella postvaginalis V-shaped, two arms short and thick, with round tip. Lamella antevaginalis trident-like, lateral arms very long, distal part bent outward and sharply pointed; middle spine reaches to 3/4 length of lateral arms, much thinner and evenly tapered into a sharp point. Apophyses posteriores very thin, about three times as long as papillae anales. Ductus bursae tube-like, long; bursa copulatrix bursiform, without signum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E1CF6787FFD2577AFF11FF093DB43D70" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A96A340CFFD2577AFF11FF093DB43D70" blockId="4.[151,1437,152,287]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">
<emphasis id="9BA1E81EFFD2577AFF11FF09383F3CDC" bold="true" box="[199,315,153,179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Remarks.</emphasis>
The female specimens were found near a stream in the tourism area of Wuzhishan (
<figureCitation id="31EE2889FFD2577AFB20FF083C4F3CDC" box="[1270,1355,152,179]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="7.[151,250,2013,2038]" captionTargetBox="[239,1348,1160,1991]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[239,1348,1160,1991]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 20. Habitat of Pedesta xiaoqingae in Wuzhishan NNR of Hainan. Photographed by Guoxi Xue." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3548634" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3548634/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
). Wing patterns of these specimens obviously exhibit sexual dimorphism. Based upon the molecular analysis in this study, they were successfully associated with the corresponding males and thus recognized as 
<taxonomicName id="6ED54F8FFFD2577AFBAAFF713C103C95" baseAuthorityName="Huang &amp; Zhan" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[1148,1300,225,250]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xiaoqingae">
<emphasis id="9BA1E81EFFD2577AFBAAFF713C103C95" box="[1148,1300,225,250]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">P. xiaoqingae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which was originally described for the genus 
<taxonomicName id="6ED54F8FFFD2577AFDC1FE943B793D71" authorityName="Swinhoe" authorityYear="1913" box="[535,637,260,286]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9BA1E81EFFD2577AFDC1FE943B793D71" box="[535,637,260,286]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Thoressa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but transferred to 
<taxonomicName id="6ED54F8FFFD2577AFC9DFE943AA03D71" authorityName="Hemming" authorityYear="1934" box="[843,932,260,286]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9BA1E81EFFD2577AFC9DFE943AA03D71" box="[843,932,260,286]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Pedesta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="CD4449FDFFD2577AFC18FE953DA83D70" author="Huang, Z. F. &amp; Chiba, H. &amp; Jin, J. &amp; Kizhakke, A. G. &amp; Wang, M. &amp; Kunte, K. &amp; Fan, X. L." box="[974,1196,260,287]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" pagination="163 - 178" refId="ref3172" refString="Huang, Z. F., Chiba, H., Jin, J., Kizhakke, A. G., Wang, M., Kunte, K. &amp; Fan, X. L. (2019) A multilocus phylogenetic framework of the tribe Aeromachini (Lepidoptera: Hesperiidae: Hesperiinae), with implications for taxonomy and biogeography. Systematic Entomology, 44, 163 - 178. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12322" type="journal article" year="2019">
Huang 
<emphasis id="9BA1E81EFFD2577AFBC9FE953D543D71" box="[1055,1104,260,286]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">et al</emphasis>
. (2019)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
